# Moving — coding conventions

These rules guide AI-generated and human-written code. Hard formatting and linting rules should live in ESLint, Prettier, and TypeScript config.

## General

* Prefer arrow functions by default.
* Use regular functions only when required by framework conventions or when they clearly improve readability.
* Use meaningful variable names. Avoid one-letter names, including loop counters.
* Prefer readable code over clever one-liners.
* Prefer early returns over nested conditionals.
* Keep files small, focused, and easy to scan.
* Split large components, hooks, services, and utilities into smaller focused files.
* Avoid premature abstractions. Extract only when duplication is real and stable.
* Follow existing project patterns before introducing new ones.
* Make small, incremental changes instead of large rewrites.

## Comments

* Do not add comments by default.
* Prefer self-documenting code through clear naming, strong typing, small functions, and good file structure.
* Add comments only when they explain context that cannot be expressed clearly in code.

Keep comments only for:

* Non-obvious business rules.
* Framework, browser, or third-party library limitations.
* Important architectural decisions.
* Real TODOs for tracked follow-up work.

When modifying existing files:

* Remove comments that restate the code.
* Remove decorative, generated, outdated, or section-separator comments.
* Remove JSX comments that only describe UI structure.
* Refactor unclear code instead of explaining it with comments.

## Architecture

Respect the project layers:

```txt
src/
  app/           Next.js routes and route handlers
  features/      Domain-specific code
  components/ui/ Shared UI primitives
  lib/           Cross-cutting infrastructure
  constants/     Shared constants
  types/         Shared types
```

Rules:

* `app/` may import from `features/`, `components/`, `lib/`, `constants/`, and `types/`.
* `features/` may import from `lib/`, `components/`, `constants/`, `types/`, and within itself.
* Avoid direct feature-to-feature imports unless there is a clear public export.
* `lib/` and `components/ui/` must not import from `features/` or `app/`.
* Server-only modules should use `import "server-only";`.

## React

* Use functional components.
* Prefer arrow functions for components.
* Prefer one main component per file.
* Use kebab-case file names and PascalCase component names.
* Keep shadcn-generated components in `components/ui/` close to their generated structure.
* Prefer composition over large components.
* Keep JSX easy to scan. Extract subcomponents when the file becomes hard to read.
* Use Server Components by default.
* Use `"use client"` only when state, effects, event handlers, or browser APIs are needed.

Example:

```tsx
type Props = {
  title: string;
};

const MyBoxes = ({ title }: Props) => {
  return <h2>{title}</h2>;
};

export default MyBoxes;
```

## Styling

* Do not use inline styles.
* Use Tailwind utilities and shared UI components.
* Use `cn()` from `@/lib/utils` for conditional classes.
* Keep styling consistent with the app theme.
* Do not fight automatic Tailwind class sorting.

## TypeScript

* Use strict typing.
* Avoid `any`. Use it only as a deliberate exception.
* Prefer `import type` for type-only imports.
* Prefer explicit return types for exported functions when it improves readability.
* Prefer `type Props = { ... }` for component props unless an interface is clearly better.

## Imports

Imports are sorted automatically by ESLint. Do not manually fight the order.

Expected order:

1. Side-effect imports.
2. React.
3. Next.js.
4. External libraries.
5. Internal infrastructure, utilities, hooks, constants, and types.
6. Feature/domain imports.
7. UI/shared component imports.
8. Relative imports.
9. Style imports.

## Data and API

* Keep route handlers thin.
* Validate inputs close to the boundary.
* Keep business logic in services or feature-level utilities.
* Keep database queries out of UI components.
* Use shared error and logging utilities instead of ad-hoc handling.

## Avoid

* Nested ternaries.
* Deep nesting.
* Large functions.
* Large JSX blocks.
* `console.log`.
* Duplicate logic.
* Unclear abbreviations.
* Mixing unrelated responsibilities in one file.
